<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920206-0041</DOCNO><DOCID>920206-0041.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Campeau Corp.:   Concern Is Unable to Keep   Document From Director</HL><DATE>02/06/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CMAFC T.CMP</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)</NS><RE>CANADA (CN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)</RE><LP>   Campeau Corp. said it failed in an attempt to block adissident director from obtaining a confidential companydocument, but said the move shouldn't affect a court hearingset for today to seek final approval for the company'srestructuring plan.   The document, a legal opinion from last year on whetherthe financially troubled Toronto real estate concern hadreason to sue its biggest creditor, Olympia andamp; YorkDevelopments Ltd., was sought by Patrick Kelly, a Campeaudirector and an associate of Robert Campeau, who was oustedas chairman in August 1990. Campeau said the legal opinion,which hadn't been given to all Campeau directors, recommendedthat no legal action be taken against Olympia andamp; York, whichis closely held by Toronto's Reichmann family.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Kelly argued in his claim that the legal opinionshould be considered by the full board before therestructuring plan receives final approval. However, anOntario Court of Justice judge ruled that the document wasn'trelevant to the restructuring plan, although he ordered thatit be released to Mr. Kelly and other directors on aconfidential basis, Campeau said.   Campeau's restructuring plan involves exchanging debt andexisting equity in the real estate concern for new shares inthe company, which will be renamed Camdev Corp.</TEXT></DOC>